s discourse. Giving voice to the Indian woman, this book also scrutinises the fiction of the first generation of western-educated Indian women who wrote in English, exploring their construction of white women and their negotiations with colonial modernities.This fascinating book will be of interest to the general reader and to experts and students of gender studies, colonial history, literary and cultural studies as well as the social history of health and medicine.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aWomenzIndiaxSocial conditionsy19th century. 0aWomenzIndiaxSocial conditionsy20th century. 0aWomen, WhitezIndiaxSocial conditionsy19th century. 0aWomen, WhitezIndiaxSocial conditionsy20th century. 4aStudies in Imperialism 2017. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  aFlora Annie Steel.  aNew Indian Women.  aayahs.  abarrack wives.  acivilising mission.  acolonial India.  acolonial household.  acolonising memsahib.  across-racial gendered interactions.  adomestic power.  amemsahib–ayah relationship.  amental health problems.  amissionaries.  anative woman.  apeasants.  asoldiers' wives.  awet-nurses.  awhite woman's vulnerability.  azenana women.1 aSen, Indrani, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2017 eBook-Packagez978311128281740uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152610601840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526106018423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526106018/original  a978-3-11-128281-7  Manchester University Press 2017 eBook-Packageb2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles